climbs.name: Young Guns
climbs.fa: unknown, FFA (lower portion): Jordy Morgan & Chris Snyder 2/88, FFA (complete route): C. Snyder, Tom Herbert & Tracy Dorton 11/88

content.description:
A bolt line located left of Bird of Fire. Intricate 5.10 face climbing leads to a headwall where very steep moves provide the crux.

Traversing right and into Bird of Fire reduces the grade to 5.10 - it's a good route though.
content.protection: 5 bolts
content.location: Descent as for Bird of Fire.

climbs.name: Young Fire
climbs.fa: unknown

content.description: Start as for Young Guns clipping the first 3 bolts and then head out right to finish on the crux of Bird of Fire.  Very good slab moves with some space between the bolts.
content.protection: 3 bolts, a couple mid or small cams with slings for the end.

climbs.name: Wings of Steel
climbs.fa: unknown, FFA: Jordy Morgan & Chris Snyder, February 1988

content.description:
Located on the smooth and attractive face just to the right of

Bird of Fire

.

Easy climbing down low leads to a sustained and technical sequence of moves starting about two-thirds of the way up the face.

Originally one of several bolt ladders on this face, it was later rebolted and led; even later the majority of bolts were removed making it a toprope for most. Two stars out of five.
content.protection: TR

climbs.name: White Mamba
climbs.fa: Bob Gaines, 1989

content.description:
This well protected sport climb that traverses left along a solid white dike is at the northwest base of the Isles in the Sky formation. Powerful lockoffs and technical footwork are essential for the duration of this very engaging climb that is only about 30' long.

The grade may be soft relative to other 5.12b climbs at J-Tree.
content.protection: This sport climb requires quickdraws for five bolts. A two bolt anchor with runners is at the end of the climb.

climbs.name: Save the Last Stance for Me
climbs.fa: Herb Laeger, Vaino Kodas & Curt Shannon, May 1986

content.description:
Climb steep plates past four bolts up and right to a bolted anchor/rap underneath the large roof. Near the top, as the angle lessens the bolts become more spaced. Not terribly runout, but it will probably keep you on your toes.

A fun climb that is fairly well bolted on steeper than usual rock and worth doing if nearby. The climb next to this (Slam Dance, 5.10c) is also worth doing.
content.protection: 4 bolts to a bolted anchor/rap (all 3/8")
content.location: Approach as normal for Isles In The Sky, but aim for a wall down and right from the portion containing Bird Of Fire. This dark wall is covered with many plates and is capped by a large roof. A short bit of scrambling leads to the base, and by scrambling up a rib just left of the wall one can easily access the base of Bird Of Fire.

climbs.name: Safety Dance
climbs.fa: Chris Miller, Dave Haber & Sheryl Haber, April 2000

content.description:
This climbs the vertical face between

Save the Last Stance for Me

and

Slam Dance

, and passes along the left side of a prominent roof midway up the face. Easily toproped from anchors atop the other routes here. Two stars out of five.
content.protection: TR

climbs.name: Slam Dance
climbs.fa: Vaino Kodas and Herb Laeger, May 1986

content.description:
Starting 15' right of

Save the Last Stance for Me

(5.9), climb past three bolts up and over a steep bulge on good holds to a shared anchor/rap with that route.

This is a very atypical route as it climb steep rock on positive holds...not your typical grainy slab. This alone is reason to give this climb a go. As a bonus this and the neighboring route are seldom done so expect the wall to yourself.
content.protection: 3 bolts to a bolted anchor/rap (all 3/8")
content.location: Down and right from the portion of Isles In The Sky with Bird Of Fire is this dark wall with many plates which is capped by a large roof.

climbs.name: Rites of Spring
climbs.fa: John Long and Mike Jaffe, May 1974

content.description: This is the first crack system to the right of Bird Of Fire.  It curves left and then straightens.  Most of the climbing is fist jamming, deep in the crack.
content.protection: standard rack, including one #3 and one #4.

climbs.name: The Raven
climbs.fa: Louie Anderson & Larry Kuechlin 4/89

content.description: Quoted from Randys guidebook......"This is a three-bolt face route up solution pockets about 100 feet right of Slam Dance." There are three bolts that are fine as they are. But above the third bolt is an obvious crack that would love to accept a #3 Camalot or it's equivalent (Too bad I did not have one with me on the climb!!!)
content.protection: There are three bolts, "button heads" and two bolts for anchors. The second bolt looks a little funky but felt solid. Currently the anchor bolts have slings and a large screw link to rap from.

climbs.name: Powder Puff Keg Stand
climbs.fa: unknown

content.description:
Bolted route from the boulders below Isle in the Sky up to the ledge. Directly below Dead Bees. 6 bolts with no anchor.

YOU MUST BRING EQUIPMENT FOR MAKING AN ANCHOR IF YOU DON'T WANT TO LEAVE YOUR PARTNER AT THE BASE.

There are two good rocks up on the ledge that make for good anchors. I used 4 120cm Nylon Runners and two locking 'biners. There is a rappel station 50 yards to the right on the ledge.
content.protection: 6 bolts. No anchor. Rappel station 50 yards to the right of the ledge.
content.location: Starts down in the boulderfield below the climb Dead Bees.

climbs.name: Nevermore
climbs.fa: unknown

content.description: Finger crack to unprotected face 12-feet right of the Raven, joins the Raven at the very end, or could traverse in earlier but for kicks try to stay independent as long as possible. Â Top rope off the Raven anchor. If there's a previous name let me know.
content.protection: I guess could be led, maybe join the Raven for bolts up higher, or stay right and independent line.

climbs.name: Nectar
climbs.fa: unknown

content.description:
This straight-in crack provides good crack practice or a nice first lead on good albeit rough rock - remember Jumbo Rocks isn't far away!

This is one sweet climb, easy but more worthwhile than some other nearby routes that are much harder; it also works as a good downclimb.
content.protection: Gear to 3 inches, bolted anchor (3/8")
content.location: Follow the trail from the parking area to the base of the wall and then third-class up any number of easy cracks to the base of this route-the first crack from the left.

climbs.name: Naked and Afraid
climbs.fa: unknown

content.description: Fun and challenging face climbing protected by bolts.
content.protection: 7 bolts to a bolted anchor.
content.location: Located right of Rites of Spring.

climbs.name: Dolphin
climbs.fa: John Long - March 1974

content.description:
Don't be fooled!  While only 5.7, Dolphin is a "classic" grovel/grunt (if you're into that sort of thing).  As one ascends, the crack widens.  Towards the top, scoot your #5 Camalot up in between mandatory cursing.

To descend, either rap Bird of Fire or walk/downclimb via 4th class ramp to the south (climber's left).
content.protection: Standard rack plus big stuff - #5 Camalot or equivalent for the top.
content.location:
Dolphin is 20' left of

Bird of Fire

.

climbs.name: Dead Bees
climbs.fa: Todd Gordon, Mike Brown, Rick McKay & Pat Brennan, April 1981

content.description: A fairly fun route that is worth doing; this climb originally had 3 bolts but was, in a rare move, retrobolted by the first ascent party to make it more accessible to climbers at this grade.
content.protection:
Climb past 5 bolts to anchors (3/8")

Walk off or rap from anchors just right of (facing the climb) Bird of Fire.
content.location:
Approximately 100 feet left of

Bird of Fire

â.

climbs.name: The Crow
climbs.fa: Don Reid and Alan Bartlett, December 1992

content.description: Climb the crack/chimney 20-feet or so right of the Raven. Ends at the Raven's anchor.
content.protection: Look up, bring gear. Raven's anchor.

climbs.name: Celebrated Beast
climbs.fa: Todd Gordon, Cyndie Bransford, Derek Reinich, KÃ¤stle Lund

content.description:
Start in a short crack which leads past a pin and upward onto the face above past three bolts ending on the ledge with Dead Bees.

Share anchors with that route and either rap off via bolts 20 feet right of Bird of Fire or do any of several down climbs available nearby.

Fun moves and good protection are in it's favor, but the large-grained rock detracts somewhat. One star out of five.
content.protection: 4 bolts, FP, gear to 2 inches, bolted anchors
content.location:
The blunt arete right of

Dead Bees

is home to this fairly well-protected and enjoyable moderate.

climbs.name: Blackbird
climbs.fa: unknown

content.description:
Starts off the 6-7' boulder to a left leaning crack, continue trending left via the path of least resistance up unprotected face/scoops and join the top of the Crow to reach the anchor bolts of the Raven.

If there's another name/ FA info before April 2021 when I climbed it, let me know and I'll add it.
content.protection: Soloed this one so not 100% sure on pro, but I think there's gear to 3" in the bottom crack and then after joining the Crow getting to the anchor is maybe fingers to 1". Could be more R rated. Standard rack should get you through.
content.location: Starts off the big boulder 15-20-feet to the right of the Crow.

climbs.name: Bird of Fire
climbs.fa: John Long & Ray Ochoa, May 1974

content.description:
Climb the stellar finger-small hands crack to the slightly bulging finish. Nice ledge just below the final 8 feet or so to rest on and get psyched out. You can see the big chalk mark from the ground. Throw in some good pro here and fire it up.

There is a 2 bolt anchor/rap (3/8") located just right of the top of this climb. Rap back to base w/one rope (70').
content.protection: Apart from the blank first 8-10 feet the pro is beautiful, a rack of nuts, and cams to gold Camalot size will have you sorted.

climbs.name: The Bee's Knees
climbs.fa: Chris Miller, Dave Haber, Sheryl Haber

content.description: Climb the rounded arete right of Bee Gees, joining that route for it's last bolt and anchors. A fun moderate route to do when in the area that is well-protected and offers a variety of steep, balancy moves.
content.protection: 5 bolts, 2 bolt anchor (all 3/8")
content.location:
Found between

Bee Gees

and

Nectar

.

climbs.name: Bee Gees
climbs.fa: Paul Neal and others, 1978

content.description:
Climb up past 2 bolts, clip a third bolt and then head right towards the edge of the block clipping a final bolt before the top. A bolted anchor is on top for a belay. To descend either walk along the top to rap bolts atop Bird of Fire or make a long roundabout walk-off the back of the wall.

Although not as good as some of the neighboring routes it does has some fun moves and provides additional mileage when in the area.
content.protection: 4 bolts, bolted anchor (all 3/8")
content.location:
On the left side of the wall a short ways left of a prominent crack (

Nectar

) and just left of

The Bee's Knees

.

climbs.name: Agoraphobia
climbs.fa: Ian McEleney and Eric Braswell, November 2010

content.description: This route climbs the water groove 25 feet right of The Raven. Follow the groove up, past the anchors for The Raven, and into a corridor on top of the formation. To descend, scramble left to the top of Bird Of Fire.
content.protection: Standard rack to #3 Camalot.
